in github, if you want to use nextflow, go to code space and run:

conda install -c bioconda nextflow

To make sure which version it is, run:

nextflow -v

Step 3: Run Nextflow in your Codespace

Navigate to your project folder (where your samplesheet.csv or workflow is).

Run a pipeline, for example:

nextflow run nf-core/viralrecon -profile conda --input samplesheet.csv --outdir results


Nextflow will automatically detect your Conda environment if you use -profile conda.



As per tutorial, the commands to run are below. See at the botton for a corrected one with less resources used.

nextflow run nf-core/viralrecon -profile conda \
--max_memory '12.GB' --max_cpus 4 \
--input samplesheet.csv \
--outdir results/viralrecon \
--protocol amplicon \
--genome 'MN908947.3' \
--primer_set artic \
--primer_set_version 3 \
--skip_kraken2 \
--skip_assembly \
--skip_pangolin \
--skip_nextclade \
--skip_asciigenome \
--platform illumina \
-resume



nextflow run nf-core/viralrecon \
  -profile conda \
  --max_memory '2.GB' \
  --max_cpus 1 \
  --input samplesheet.csv \
  --outdir results/viralrecon \
  --protocol amplicon \
  --genome 'MN908947.3' \
  --primer_set artic \
  --primer_set_version 3 \
  --skip_kraken2 \
  --skip_assembly \
  --skip_pangolin \
  --skip_nextclade \
  --skip_asciigenome \
  --platform illumina \
  -resume \
  --save_report false \
  --save_logs false \
  --save_metadata false \
  --save_trace false \
  --save_workflow false
